I am so, so tired of hearing “white privilege.” Because I grew up in a wealthy area with parents that were successful (because they worked their asses off) doesn’t mean I AM. What a lot of people don’t realize is that people like me, who grow up in successful families, we’re not handed A THING! My dad grew up dirt poor & achieved success because he worked HARD. And he had the same attitude, still does, with me; if I wanted something, I had to work for it. That’s why I was the youngest Avon rep in history - it’s the only job I could get that young. I’ve worked since I was a teen. My parents provided the basics, but if I wanted those James Jeans all the girls were wearing...I had to earn the money & save to buy them.

In addition, it’s not only “white people” who grow up like this. My best friend all through middle and high school was black and her family was the same - very successful, hard-working - and they raised her the same; she was taught to work hard in school & to set goals and work hard to achieve them. It doesn’t matter the color of your skin or how you start out - as I said, my dad (white) was poorer than poor. But he wanted out of that poverty, set goals, got his GED, went to college and worked his ass off, becoming a top business owner in Seattle. It’s due to GOALS AND HARD WORK.

When he was selling newspapers on the corner (and fighting to retain that corner) on Sandy Blvd (in Portland) when he was a kid, he saved every nickel he made. He didn’t buy crap he didn’t need. He saved to survive and never gave up. To this day, regardless of his wealth, he lives like the poor kid he once was. He just not bought a new fridge because the old one (35 years OLD) finally gave out. Even then, he called all the family to see if anyone had an old fridge he could have! LOL! Truly wealthy people are that way because THEY WORK HARD & SAVE. That’s how they retain their wealth.

Raised with this attitude, I’ve set my goals & worked my ass off for what I have. My dad, to this day, has never given me a DIME. Not a dime. Even when I was flat broke, electricity off, rent due, etc. he told me to figure it out, start saving my money, live on a budget and I wouldn’t be there again. While there may be some who have wealthy families where they don’t live like this, most of the ones I grew up with do because our families knew what it took to get there and giving it to your kids, not teaching them the value of work and saving...that’s not how to get there.

Liberia (/laɪˈbɪəriə/), officially the Republic of Liberia, is a country on the West African coast. It is bordered by Sierra Leone to its northwest, Guinea to its north, Ivory Coast to its east, and the Atlantic Ocean to its south-southwest. It has a population of around 5 million and covers an area of 111,369 square kilometres (43,000 sq mi). English is the official language, but over 20 indigenous languages are spoken, representing the numerous ethnic groups who make up more than 95% of the population. The country's capital and largest city is Monrovia.

 Liberia began as a settlement of the American Colonization Society (ACS), who believed black people would face better chances for freedom and prosperity in Africa than in the United States. The country declared its independence on July 26, 1847. The U.S. did not recognize Liberia's independence until February 5, 1862, during the American Civil War. Between January 7, 1822, and the American Civil War, more than 15,000 freed and free-born black people who faced legislated limits in the U.S., and 3,198 Afro-Caribbeans, relocated to the settlement. The settlers carried their culture and tradition with them. The Liberian constitution and flag were modeled after those of the U.S. On January 3, 1848, Joseph Jenkins Roberts, a wealthy, free-born African American from Virginia who settled in Liberia, was elected Liberia's first president after the people proclaimed independence.

Let me explain further why I disagree with censorship.
I am a writer. The things that I have created may imply many unjust things, and may imply that I agree with them. I am merely a writer. I don't weave real world politics into my stories. It is wrong to mix entertainment and politics, as it stokes the fires of polarization in our country and only makes our troubles worse.
Censorship is also inherently counterproductive. We live in a society that has promised all of us that we can say whatever we want, and yet when we do it is apparently wrong to do so. Censorship is a backwards idea that borders the dangers of socialism, which is a political ideology that I don't agree with for many more reasons.
So, I respectfully disagree. Growing up I was told that if I was hurt, then I should forgive those who hurt me and deal with it. Growing up I was told that if I was in pain, then I should accept it and deal with it. I am also a technical cripple. I live in a constant state of pain. But I deal with it.
Today it appears we live in a snowflake culture. Growing up people were told that if they were hurt then they must not only whine about it, they must get revenge.
This may sound like the viewpoint of an old conservative, but let me make myself clearer.
I am seventeen years old, and I have a larger dose of reality than most of my peers because I live in constant pain.
I don't wish to censor a comedian because he or she may make a joke about a cripple. In fact, I laugh with them. Because it's all in good fun.

@Miss Jae, I don't believe that any one person is high and mighty. Or any cause, for that matter. I don't have to see anything to know that.
And if they "made fun of" this transgender person, jokes are jokes. Comedy is inherently offensive; it's part of human nature.

Consequences for what anyone says or does is a must. These twins will deal with whatever consequences they come across for their words and actions, but that doesn't give anyone the right to censor their content and put limits on what they can say.
I suppose that I just try to be practical. I can be sorry that someone's feelings are hurt, but I can't support censorship or cancel culture.

White Privilege isn't real. It may have been real many decades ago, but not today. Before my grandparents passed away, they had a lot of money saved up. We never knew how much, it wasn't our place to ask. When my grandmother passed, she left behind a lot of money and a nice house. Some out there would say they had the wealth they had handed to them. It couldn't be further from the truth. My grandparents met when they were young. They dated, then married as soon as they legally could. My grandfather's brother lived in New York State and let them move in with him. Well, not in his house though. He had a storage shed full of old furniture, a small bed, a small circular table with two flimsy wooden chairs. The storage shed was originally a chicken coop. So chicken coop to storage shed, then storage shed to barely a house. They could draw water from a well, use the outhouse, and I believe use the shower to bathe. They started working and one of them worked in a factory canning peaches while the other worked in a processing plant making lunch meats. They could buy bologna, ham, etc. with an employee discount. The other would occasionally dent cans of peaches so they could take them home to eat. They spent what little money they had on only what they needed to survive. Bread, milk, etc.

Eventually, my grandfather got a job in construction. He learned the trade and had an employer who trained him and got him certified. He learned how to build houses to make money AND learn how to build his own home (I'm living in the house he built when my mother was a little girl). My grandmother got a job working at a gas station and learned how to run it. She worked her way up to manager and learned how to do inventory and all the paperwork involved in running a business. With the experience she gained, she worked hard to get a business license. She used that experience to open her own Mom and Pop general store. They didn't pull in tons of money, but they made a profit. She worked every day as long as I could remember, aside from one vacation to Virginia Beach when I was a child.

My grandfather joined McNeil Fence Company and worked his way up to foreman. He worked hard at what he did and earned the respect of the company owner. If a job was going to be difficult, he would get my grandfather. He worked a full-time job AND built fences for people on the side. He built his own home when my mother was a little girl; adding on to the house as needed over the years. By the time my grandfather retired, his hands were nearly crippled from arthritis and hundreds of old injuries. I always remembered the dent in his palm, as if someone pressed the skin down with a pencil, but the skin stayed there. Doctors had to use wire on broken bones to fix his hand from an injury.

By the time both had retired, they saved up hundreds of thousands of dollars. They lived dirt poor in their youth and saved everything they could over the 50+ years they spent married. They even had emergency money locked away in safety deposit boxes. My grandfather had an old coffee can with hundreds of dollars worth of bills and coins that he would occasionally count. Just having that in his closet helped him feel secure; That he wasn't going to be dirt poor again.

Still reading? Does it sound like everything they had was handed to them on a silver platter?

Racist this Racist that, they're a racist because the source that is my own news station said so... tearing down statues and wanting to rewrite history so that no one knows anything anymore about the roots of our country and what we've come from because they're just sooooo offended by everything. I come from a religion and blood heritage... where my people, from the 1830's and through early 1900's were openly killed raped, abused, robbed, and murdered until they had to just flee west and establish their own communities there in peace... It was not against the law because they were not deemed the same as people... A dog's live was considered more valuable, and there was no difference between shooting a horse and shooting a Latter-Day Saint. They were the first to become pioneers, flee Missouri, and the eastern stats of America (not yet the USA), and settled states from there all the way to California.

I'm not running around saying "WHERE'S MY JUSTICE!!! THE JUSTICE I'VE HAD ISN'T GOOD ENOUGH!!!" What I am, is grateful to them for weathering that Hell, and leaving lessons I could learn from and use to my advantage and prosper in my day. Now I'm going to make a comparison... Although my ancestors weren't esnlaved and working cotton fields they still had it pretty bad starting out in this country just as they did... those who survived that trial had children, and those children grew up and had children, and now here I am and here you are, referring to African Americans, and I will boldly claim you, nor I went through the same thing our ancestors did, yet there are those among us who are so angry about it they have to run around making a big scene, rallying, saying how oppressed they are, and they'll never be able to get ahead in life because of their oppression. We have pioneer day to honor my ancestors, you have black history month to honor yours, and as a nation we honor them together because they helped make this land a place truly free of oppression of race and religion... and yet here these people are on t.v. trying to jettison this country into the next level of racism, anarchy, and prejudice. Why? I'm genuinely asking... Why?

I don't believe these are the majority, who we see on t.v. I hope and believe they are the minority because all I know is my African American friends don't act like that, and we don't say my white friend or my black friend (although we do sometimes for the sake of poking fun at the rest of the nation right now...)… we're just friends.
